05811nam a22008775i 9780231511773DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979967632  a97802315117737 a10.7312/lako146062doi  a(DE-B1597)459036  a(OCoLC)647929688  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aRA441 .B56 7aMED0350002bisacsh04a614.4400aBiosecurity Interventions :bGlobal Health and Security in Question /ced. by Stephen Collier, Andrew Lakoff. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA Columbia / SSRC Book00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- t1. The problem of securing health -- t2. From population to vital system -- t3. Redesigning syndromic surveillance for biosecurity -- t4. How did the smallpox vaccination program come about? -- t5. Disease as security threat -- t6. Vital mobility and the humanitarian kit -- t7. Mapping the multiplicities of biosecurity -- t8. From mad cow disease to bird flu -- t9. Biodefense -- t10. Anticipations of biosecurity -- tAfterword: Episodes or incidents -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, new disease threatssuch as SARS, avian flu, mad cow disease, and drug-resistant strains of malaria and tuberculosishave garnered media attention and galvanized political response. Proposals for new approaches to "securing health" against these threats have come not only from public health and medicine but also from such fields as emergency management, national security, and global humanitarianism. This volume provides a map of this complex and rapidly transforming terrain. The editors focus on how experts, public officials, and health practitioners work to define what it means to "secure health" through concrete practices such as global humanitarian logistics, pandemic preparedness measures, vaccination campaigns, and attempts to regulate potentially dangerous new biotechnologies.As the contributions show, despite impressive activity in these areas, the field of "biosecurity interventions" remains unstable. Many basic questions are only beginning to be addressed: Who decides what counts as a biosecurity problem? Who is responsible for taking action, and how is the efficacy of a given intervention to be evaluated? It is crucial to address such questions today, when responses to new problems of health and security are still taking shape. In this context, this volume offers a form of critical and reflexive knowledge that examines how technical efforts to increase biosecurity relate to the political and ethical challenges of living with risk.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiological warfarexPrevention. 0aBioterrorismxPrevention. 0aCommunicable diseasesxPrevention. 0aNational security. 0aWorld health. 7aMEDICAL / Health Care Delivery.2bisacsh1 aBingham, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaduff, Carlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollier, Stephen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollier, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFearnley, Lyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinchliffe, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeck, Frédéric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLakoff, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLakoff, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabul